Phase 6 Part 9 - Final QA: security audit re-pass over Parts 4-8

Part 2 (docs/phase-6-part2-security-audit.md) already covered
authentication/authorization/rate-limiting/SQLi/XSS/CSRF/SSRF/CORS/
secrets/OWASP for the whole system through Part 1. This pass specifically
re-examined everything ADDED in Parts 4 through 8 for the same categories,
rather than re-running the entire original audit a second time.

Real finding + fix:
- metrics.routes.ts (Part 4) compared the Authorization header against
  the expected bearer token with plain `!==` instead of this codebase's
  established timingSafeEqual pattern (already used in JwtTokenService.ts
  and both payment gateways' webhook signature checks). A `!==` string
  comparison leaks how many leading bytes matched via response timing --
  low real-world severity here (an internal metrics token, not a
  high-value credential) but inconsistent with how every other secret
  comparison in this app is written, and cheap to fix correctly. FIXED:
  now buffers both sides, checks length first (timingSafeEqual throws on
  a length mismatch rather than returning false), then timingSafeEqual.
  Verified standalone: 6/6 checks pass (correct token accepted, wrong
  token rejected, missing header rejected, different-length token
  rejected without throwing, unset METRICS_TOKEN leaves the endpoint
  open as documented, empty-string header rejected).

Reviewed, no issues found:
- Sentry/NoOp error tracker (Part 4): SentryErrorTracker's captured
  payload includes requestId/userId/route/method/statusCode and an
  `extra` bag the caller controls -- errorHandler.ts only ever passes
  those five specific fields, never the raw request body or headers, so
  no risk of a payment/auth payload leaking into a third-party error
  tracking service via this path.
- Backup/restore scripts (Part 5): DATABASE_URL is read from the
  environment, never hardcoded or logged; restore-db.sh requires typing
  "restore" to confirm before running --clean (destructive) against
  whatever DATABASE_URL happens to be set to.
- CI/CD (Part 6): GITHUB_TOKEN used for the GHCR push has its default,
  auto-scoped, run-limited permissions (packages: write only, explicitly
  set) rather than a long-lived PAT; deploy.yml's SSH credentials are
  GitHub Secrets, never echoed in any step. Docker prod images (Part 6)
  run as the non-root `node` user in both Dockerfiles.
- .gitignore (Part 6): fixed during that pass already -- .env.production
  was not previously matched by any ignore rule (only .env.production.local
  was) and could have been committed with real production secrets in it.
  Re-verified in this pass with `git check-ignore`: .env/.env.production/
  .env.local all still correctly ignored, .env.example/.env.production.example/
  backend/.env.example all still correctly tracked.
- Capacitor config (Part 7): androidScheme/iosScheme set to "https" (not
  Capacitor's default "http" on Android), no secrets embedded in
  capacitor.config.ts or the native project scaffold instructions.
- Service worker (Part 7): re-confirmed it never intercepts non-GET
  requests, same-origin /api/ paths, or cross-origin requests -- so it
  cannot serve stale/cached responses for any auth, payment, or messaging
  endpoint (originally verified in Part 7, re-checked here in the
  security-audit context specifically).
- Deployment guides (Part 8): all example credentials/keys in every guide
  are placeholders (your-api-key, replace_with_a_64_byte_random_hex_secret,
  etc.); guides explicitly recommend separate credentials per environment
  and least-privilege API key restrictions (Google Maps IP-restriction,
  Cloudinary separate accounts) rather than reusing one set of credentials
  across dev/staging/production.

No other new issues found in this pass.
